{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d4ddf872-78f3-4e85-8f08-14d256a21cb8","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_fqoJlCIJnFKOUhzFfwvJor","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Researching .NET MAUI Java issue"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_D8r6kjlBe9a3NSkja0Tx34","name":"glob","arguments":{"pattern":"plugins/**/*"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"plugins/**/*"}],"interactionId":"d7da0d18-3f28-4960-8787-e3e55131d7c1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed and JAVA_HOME points to it.\n\nThis is a known issue with .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds. The problem is likely that the .NET Android SDK has a specific requirement for the Java JDK version and path.\n\nLet me think about common issues:\n\n1. **JAVA_HOME path on macOS for Adoptium Temurin**: On macOS, Adoptium Temurin installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`. The user needs to make sure JAVA_HOME points to the correct path.\n\n\n2. **JDK version compatibility**: .NET MAUI / .NET Android requires JDK 11 or JDK 17, so JDK 17.0.12 should work fine.\n3. **The real culprit**: The .NET Android build system doesn't always respect the system JAVA_HOME variable. Instead, it uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, which might be pointing to a different JDK installation or the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with Visual Studio for Mac or the .NET Android workload.\n4. **Path resolution on macOS**: Adoptium Temurin JDK typically installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but the .NET Android SDK might not find it there or could have compatibility issues with that specific distribution, which is why explicitly setting the Java path in the `.csproj` file or via command line often becomes necessary. JDK 17**, and specifically the Microsoft distribution of OpenJDK 17 is recommended. However, Adoptium Temurin should also work.\n\nLet me think about what the actual problem might be...\n\nActually, I think the most likely issue here is one of these:\n\n1. **The .NET Android SDK doesn't respect JAVA_HOME by default** - it has its own logic for finding Java. You need to explicitly set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in your project file or pass it as an MSBuild property.\n\n2. **On macOS with .NET 8+**, the recommended approach is to install the Microsoft OpenJDK via the Android workload: `dotnet workload install android` which includes the Microsoft build of OpenJDK.\n\n3. **A very specific known issue**: .NET MAUI Android builds on macOS may fail if JAVA_HOME contains spaces or if the path format is wrong.\n\nThe real culprit is usually that the .NET Android SDK looks in specific hardcoded locations rather than just checking JAVA_HOME, so either installing Microsoft's OpenJDK through the workload or explicitly setting `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project file typically resolves the issue. On macOS with Adoptium Temurin, the path to set `JAVA_HOME` should point to the JDK installation directory, and I can pass that explicitly to the .NET build system if needed. Let me check if there's anything in this repository related to .NET or Android builds that might be relevant to this issue.","outputTokens":1408,"requestId":"482E:3387D:5202169:5A2B6EC:69F3FAB3"},"id":"a4ac37aa-ec41-4605-983a-1ca9e7fdda1b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:58:53.746Z","parentId":"2e495a4e-e74e-42d3-96ec-1293a76adca6"}
